[[File:Orihata-jinja (Munakata), torii.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii}}{{small|Mount Sayagata in the back. }}]]
'''Orihata Shrine'' (Orihata Jinja) is located in {{ill|lt=Fukuoka Prefecture|Q123258|WD=Q123258|1=Fukuoka Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Munakata City|Q819603|WD=Q819603|1=Munakata, Fukuoka}}{{ill|lt=Kanezaki (Munakata City)|Q11651333|WD=Q11651333|lt=Kanezaki|1=Kanezaki}}.

{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinai Shrine|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}}, {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}, and {{ill|lt=Modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

Another name is "Orihataguu". Locals also call him ``Shikihan-sama''.

=== Enshrined God ===
The following seven deities are enshrined {{Sfn|Kamigun Munakata No. 1|2011|p=8}}.
:* Minister Takeuchi (Takeuchi no Oomi) - {{ill|lt=Takeuchi Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}}
:* {{ill|lt=Sumiyoshi Three Gods|Q1114013|WD=Q1114013|lt=Sumiyoshi Okami|1=Sumiyoshi sanjin}} (Sumiyoshi no Okami)
:* Shiga Okami
:* {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Omikami|Q455602|WD=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}} (Amaterasu no Okami)
:* Munakata no Okami
:* Kashii no Okami
:* {{ill|lt=Hachimankami|Q261637|WD=Q261637|lt=Hachiman Okami|1=Hachiman}} (Hachiman no Okami)
:* {{ill|lt=Maneko Iki|UNKNOWN|lt=Maneko Iki}}In "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, which was established in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), there is one enshrined deity. At the time of ``Munakata Daibosatsu Goengi,'' which was established during the {{ill|lt=Bunan|Q1193586|WD=Q1193586|1=Bun'an}} years ({{ill|lt=1444|Q6420|WD=Q6420|1=1444}}-{{ill|lt=1449|Q6446|WD=Q6446|1=1449}}), it is written that Minister Takeuchi is the enshrined deity, and {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine )|2000}}, {{ill|lt=Early Modern Period|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}}'s ``{{ill|lt=Chikuzen Kunitsoku Fudoki|Q108571667|WD=Q108571667|1=Chikuzen no Kuni Zoku Fudoki}}'' states that the three deities enshrined here are Takeuchi Minister, Sumiyoshi Okami, and Shiga Okami.{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1978}}. Currently, the eight deities listed above are enshrined, and the three main deities are Takeuchi Minister, Sumiyoshi Okami, and Shiga Okami {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine History Book, Orihata Shrine|2025}}.During the {{ill|lt=Shinbutsu syncretization|Q2279088|WD=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}} period, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Honjibutsu|1=UNKNOWN}} was considered to be {{ill|lt=Nyoirin Kannon|Q11446712|WD=Q11446712|1=Cintāmaṇicakra}} {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. {{ill|lt=Munakata Taisha|Q704962|WD=Q704962|1=Munakata Taisha}} Formerly {{ill|lt=Jinguji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}} {{ill|lt=Chinkokuji|Q11651157|WD=Q11651157|1=Chinkoku-ji}}, the original Buddhist statues of the five Munakata shrines (Fukuoka Prefecture-designated cultural properties) including Orihata Shrine have been preserved for generations. <ref>{{PDFlink|[http://city.munakata.lg.jp/w009/050/140/0010/130/13-14shinaisiteibunkazai-shuusei.pdf Cultural properties in the city]}} (Munakata City homepage). </ref>.

=== About the enshrined deity ===
The theory that the enshrined deity of Orihata Shrine is Takeuchi Sukune (Minister Takeuchi) dates back to ``Munakata Daibosatsu Goengi,'' which was established in the middle of the {{ill|lt=15th century|Q7018|WD=Q7018|1=15th century}}, and the same Engi records the founding tradition described below ({{ill|lt=#Sōken|UNKNOWN|lt=Sōken-bushi}}). On the other hand, the precincts of Orihata Shrine are located at Cape Kaneno, a strategic point that juts out into the sea, and the entire area is also identified as ``Kaifu-go'' in ``{{ill|lt=Japanese name Ruijusho|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542|lt=Japanese namebook|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}'', indicating that Kaifu existed there. Because of its location in the region, there is a theory that it was originally a sea god worshiped by the Kaijin tribe. As mentioned below ({{ill|lt=#tradition|UNKNOWN|lt=tradition section}}), "{{ill|lt=Manyoshu|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}" <ref group="Hara" name="Manyoshu"/>When passing Cape Kaneno, there is a shrine called "Shiga no Kojin" ({{ill|lt=Shigaumi Shrine|Q11491171|WD=Q11491171|1=Shikaumi Shrine}}Enshrined deity: {{jalink|Aduji|Q3377806} }There is also a theory that the Azumi clan (Adu tribe), a member of the Kaijin tribe, resided in the area and worshiped the Shiga god, as there is a song that says they pray to the god Hosai.{{Sfn|Kanasaki/Kanezaki (Heibonsha)|2004}}Also, "{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}" {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}} era<ref group="Hara" name="Emperor Ojin 37th year">"Nihon Shoki" Article dated February 1, 1997 of Emperor Ojin, article of February 41, 41st year of Emperor Ojin. In </ref>, the Emperor ordered {{ill|lt=Achi Messenger|Q11657596|WD=Q11657596|1=Achi no Omi}} and {{ill|lt=Tuka Messenger|Q24863564|WD=Q24863564|1=Tuka Messenger}} to go to Wu (Kangnan, China) and obtain sewing women, but when the Achi Messengers returned home, they were told that they had ``Chunkagata Okami'' (= There is a legend that he offered his older brother among the four female factory workers to the god Munakata Okami) at the request of the god Munakata Okami. </ref>, there is also a theory that connects this tradition with Orihata Shrine. Among these theories, it is pointed out that the weavers who weave clothes to offer to the gods may have been deified.{{Sfn|Munakata City History In General History Volume 2 | 1999 | pp=31-33}}, it is pointed out that Takeuchi Sukune may have been chosen as the enshrined deity as the common ancestor of the imported clans that were responsible for weaving {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Gods) | 2000}}.Of the eight deities enshrined, Maneko Iki is said to be the founder of the {{ill|lt=Iki clan|Q11429628|WD=Q11429628|1=Iki clan}}, the former chief priest of Orihata Shrine {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1978}}. In addition to the existence of the Iki clan, the "Otenaga" that appears in the "Munakata Daibosatsu Engi" is {{ill|lt=Iki Island|Q494914|WD=Q494914|1=Iki Island}}'s Shikinai Shrine {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amante Nagao Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}・Since it is also associated with Amante Nagahime Shrine, there is a theory that suggests a relationship between the rituals at Orihata Shrine and Iki Island.{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1978}}.

In addition, there are different theories about the deity enshrined, such as the theory that it is Oomikutsu no Kami, and the theory that it is Kureori or Anaori.{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Gods)|2000}}.

=== History ===
[[File:Kanezaki Port 01.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Distant view of Cape Kanezaki}}{{small|View from Kanezaki fishing port. Orihata Shrine is located halfway up Mt. Sayagata on the far left of the image. }}]]

=== Founding ===
Regarding its founding, according to "Munakata Daibosatsu Goengi" (established in the mid-15th century), during the {{ill|lt=Empress Jingu|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}} {{ill|lt=Conquest of the Three Koreas|Q11249435|WD=Q11249435|1=Three Han Campaign}}, the Minister of Munakata ({{jal ink|Munakata Taisha|Q704962}}) fought with two red and white flags woven by Minister Takeuchi ({{ill|lt=Takeuchi Sukune|Q1073668|WD=Q1073668|1=Takenouchi no Sukune}}) attached to a flagpole called ``Otenaga'', and in the end, they were used as ``Soku Mishima (= It was built on {{ill|lt=Okinoshima|Q7082047|WD=Q7082047|1=Okinoshima (Fukuoka)}}). At the time of Minister Takeuchi's funeral, the spirit was enshrined on the seashore to protect the sea route from invading pirates, and it was named ``Orihata (Orihata)'' because Minister Takeuchi wove the flag.{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1978}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.

The actual establishment is not known, but as mentioned above, there are theories that suggest a relationship with the Kaijin tribe, {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Kadokawa)|1988}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Gods)|2000}}, "Nihon Shoki" <ref group="Hara" There is a theory that speculates that there is a relationship between {{ill|lt=Achi Messenger|Q11657596|WD=Q11657596|1=Achi no Omi}} of name="Emperor Ojin's 37th year"/> and the legend of the seamstress of the Munakata deity.{{Sfn|Munakata City History General History Volume 2|1999|pp=31-33}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Gods)|2000}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.

=== Outline ===
In {{ill|lt=Rokukokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|lt=Kokushi|1=Rikkokushi}}, {{ill|lt=Kaxiang|Q1373157|WD=Q1373157|1=Kashō}}3 years ({{ill|lt=850 years|Q30364|WD=Q30364|1=850}}) <ref group="Hara" name="Kasho 3rd year"/> In addition to the article that "Orihatakami" is given the rank of Jigoinoge, {{ill|lt=Shinkai|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}}, {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} 3rd year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}) <ref group="Hara" name="Jogan 1st year"/>Junior Fifth Rank, {{ill|lt=Genkei|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}}1st year ({{ill|lt=877|Q23905|WD=Q23905|1=877}})<ref group="Hara" You can see an article stating that he was promoted to the lower rank of Shogoi in name="Genkoi 1"/>{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1978}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.{{ill|lt=extension (era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=extended|1=Enchō}} "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" established in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927 years|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) {{jali nk|Engishiki Shrine Name Book|Q11064932|Shin Name Book}}, {{ill|lt=Chikuzen Province|Q1047664|WD=Q1047664|1=Chikuzen Province}}{{ill|lt=Munakata District|Q6935606|WD=Q6935606|1=Munakata District, Fukuoka}} has ``Orihata Shrine'' It is listed as {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} along with Munakata Shrine 3 (currently Munakata Taisha) (Munakata County The only Shikinai shrines are Munakata Shrine and Orihata Shrine) {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1978}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. Among the place names that appear in "{{ill|lt=Wamyo Ruijusho|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542|lt=Wamyo Sho|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}" from the middle of the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} According to one theory, this area is located in Kaifu-go, Munakata District. It is presumed that around this Heian period, Orihata Shrine became a shrine under the jurisdiction of Munakata Shrine.According to the Dajokan Code draft of {{ill|lt=Bun'ei|Q1010103|WD=Q1010103|1=Bun'ei}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1265|Q5516|WD=Q5516|1=1265}}), at that time the {{jali nk|Chinkokuji|Q11651157}} {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Honjibutsu|1=UNKNOWN}} of ``Kanezaki Orihata Myojin'' was enshrined {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1978}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. Also, in the {{ill|lt=Kishōmon|Q11636131|WD=Q11636131|1=kishōmon}} of Bun'ei 9 ({{ill|lt=1272|Q5524|WD=Q5524|1=1272}}), ``Orihata Daimyojin'' appears {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. Established in {{ill|lt=Bunan|Q1193586|WD=Q1193586|1=Bun'an}} ({{ill|lt=1444|Q6420|WD=Q6420|1=1444}}-{{ill|lt=1449|Q6446|WD=Q6446|1=1449}}) In ``Munakata Daibosatsu Goengi,'' the five gods of Munakata, plus Orihata Daimyojin and Kōgi Gongen, are collectively called the ``Munakata Five Shrines'' {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.After {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), {{j alink|Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534}} Ranked as {{ill|lt=Murasha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1978 }}, in Meiji 15 ({{ill|lt=1882|Q7812|WD=Q7812|1=1882}}), {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Showa|1=UNKNOWN}}3 ({{ill|lt=1928|Q19715|WD=Q19715|1=1928}}), it was promoted to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}{{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1978}}.

In the 10th year of the Meiji era ({{ill|lt=1877|Q7773|WD=Q7773|1=1877}}), Munakata Shrine (currently Munakata Taisha Shrine) reported it to the government as a separate shrine along with Matohara Shrine, Kodaiji Shrine, Miyajidake Shrine, and others.

=== God level ===
* July 29, 3rd year of {{ill|lt=Kasho|Q1373157|WD=Q1373157|1=Kashō}} ({{ill|lt=850 years|Q30364|WD=Q30364|1=850}}), Jugoinoge ("{{ill|lt=Nihon Montoku Emperor Annals|Q1052905|WD=Q1052905|1=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku}}") <ref group="Hara" name="Kasho 3rd year">"Japanese Emperor Montoku Annals" July 29th Kasho 3rd year (850) article (see {{Harvnb|Shinto and Shrine Historical Materials Collection}}). </ref> - The spelling is "Orihatakami".
* {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} January 27, 3rd year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), from the lower junior fifth rank to the upper junior fifth rank ("{{ill|lt=Japan Sandai Jiroki|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}") <ref group="Hara" name="Jōgan 1st year">"Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku" Article dated 27th New Year, Jogan 1st year (859) (see {{Harvnb|Shinto and Shrine Historical Materials Collection}}). </ref> - The spelling is "Orihatakami".
* December 15th, {{ill|lt=Genkei|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 1st year ({{ill|lt=877|Q23905|WD=Q23905|1=877}}), from Jugoinoge {{sub|Mama}} to Shogoikege (``Nihon Sandai Jirroku'') <ref group="Hara" name="Genko 1st year">"Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku" December 15th, Genkei 1st year (877) (see {{Harvnb|Shinto and Shrine Historical Materials Collection}}). </ref> - The name is written as "Orihatakami."

=== Shinto priest ===
The rituals at Orihata Shrine are said to have been carried out by {{ill|lt=Iki clan|Q11429628|WD=Q11429628|1=Iki clan}} {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1978}}. According to legend, this Iki clan is said to be a descendant of the enshrined deity Maneko Iki, and when the Heike clan fell, they changed their surname from "Iki" to "Irie," but {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Bunkyu|1=UNKNOWN}} ({{ill|lt=1863|Q7701|WD=Q7701|1=1863}}) {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1978}}. After that, the Iki family retired from the position of chief priest of Orihata Shrine in {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}18 ({{ill|lt=1943|Q18623|WD=Q18623|1=1943}}) {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1978}}.

=== Precincts ===
[[File:Orihata-jinja (Munakata), shaden.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Shrine building}}{{small|The main shrine is on the left, and the worship hall is on the right. }}]]The precincts are located halfway up Mt. Sayakata, at the tip of Cape Kaneno, which separates {{ill|lt=Genkai Sea|Q498047|WD=Q498047|1=Genkai Sea}} and {{ill|lt=Hibikinada|Q11288861|WD=Q11288861|1=Hibiki Sea}}. A temperate forest has formed within the grounds of Orihata Shrine and on Mt. Sayakata, including more than 10 giant trees of {{ill|lt=Inumaki|Q165063|WD=Q165063|1=Podocarpus macrophyllus}}, {{ill|lt=Chii|Q1065400|WD=Q1065400|1=Castanopsis}}, {{jalink|Hamanabiwa|Q1258941} 4}}・{{ill|lt=Yabunikai|Q161335|WD=Q161335|1=Cinnamomum pedunculatum}}・{{ill|lt=Sangoju|Q12600081|WD=Q12600081|1=Viburnum odoratissimum}}・{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Onore|1=UNKNOWN}}・{{ill|lt=Shirodamo|Q5792530|WD=Q5792530|1=Neolitsea sericea}}・{{ill|lt=Tabnoki|Q5792073|WD=Q5792073|lt=Tab|1=Machilus thunbergii}}・{{ill|lt=Tobera|Q161375|WD=Q161375|1=Pittosporum tobira}}・{{ill|lt=Yatsude|Q203569|WD=Q203569|1=Fatsia japonica}}・{{ill|lt=Tsubaki|Q160121|WD=Q160121|1=Camellia japonica}}・{{ill|lt=Yuzuriha|Q846968|WD=Q846968|1=Daphniphyllum macropodum}}・{{ jalink|Yamamomo|Q311617}}・{{ill|lt=Sanekazura|Q1441971|WD=Q1441971|1=Kadsura japonica}}・{{ill|lt=Fouto Kazura|Q5924111|WD=Q5924111|1=Piper kadsura}}・{{ill|lt=Sakaki|Q775470|WD=Q775470|1=Cleyera japonica}}・{{ill|lt=Aoki (Plants) More than 20 species grow here, including|Q163114|WD=Q163114|lt=Aoki|1=Aucuba japonica}}, {{ill|lt=Masaki|Q161383|WD=Q161383|1=Euonymus japonicus}}, {{ill|lt=Kijoorchid|Q5367121|WD=Q5367121|lt=Kijoorchid|1=Marsdenia tomentosa}}, and {{ill|lt=Mukunoki|Q4779482|WD=Q4779482|1=Aphananthe aspera}}. This natural forest has been designated as a natural monument of Fukuoka Prefecture as the ``Orihata Shrine Inumaki Natural Forest'' (Munahaku Electronic Museum). </ref>.According to ancient documents, the current main shrine was built in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}}8 ({{ill|lt=1695|Q7696|WD=Q7696|1=1695}}), and the worship hall was built in Genroku 16 ({{ill|lt=1703|Q6822|WD=Q6822|1=1703}}). Several other companies are also located within the precincts.

Also within the precincts are Kutsuzuka, where the enshrined deity, Minister Takeuchi, buried the shoe left after ascending to heaven, {{Sfn|Orihata Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1978}}, and a huge stone related to the legend of the sinking bell, which will be described later.
