=== Cultural assets ===

=== Fukuoka Prefecture designated cultural property ===
* Natural monument
** Inumaki natural forest at Orihata Shrine - Designated on August 13, 1955<ref name="Explanation board">Explanation board within the precincts. </ref>.

=== Tradition ===
[[File:Orihata-jinja (Munakata), kyoseki.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Giant stone of the legend of the sunken bell}}]]
There is a legend that a foreign bell is sunk in the sea at Cape Kanenomisaki, where Orihata Shrine is located. The place name ``Cape Kaneno'' comes from this, and similar legends of sinking bells are known all over the country, but this area and Kanegasaki in {{ill|lt=Fukui Prefecture|Q133879|WD=Q133879|1=Fukui Prefecture}} are especially famous <ref name="Complete Works of Japanese Classical Literature"/>. However, what was thought to be a bell on the sea floor at Cape Kaneno was brought back to land in {{ill|lt=Taisho|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}}8 ({{ill|lt=1919|Q2157|WD=Q2157|1=1919}}), but what was pulled up at that time was not a bell but a megalith<ref name="Explanation board"/>. This megalith is currently enshrined on the approach to Orihata Shrine.

Additionally, the area between Cape Kaneno and {{ill|lt=Jijima|Q17992764|WD=Q17992764|1=Jinoshima}} on the opposite shore is a reef area, and it is known that it has been a key point and difficult point for maritime transportation since ancient times. "{{ill|lt=Manyoushu|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}" <ref group="Hara" name="Manyoushu">Manyoushu volume 7 number 1230 ([http://infux03.inf.edu.yamaguchi-u.ac.jp/~manyou/ver2_2/manyou_kekka2.php?kekka=07/1230 07/1230] <Yamaguchi University "Man'yoshu Search System"> reference). </ref>So,{{Cquote|Chihayaburu Even if I don't pass the golden cape, I won't forget Shiga's Emperor (Sumekami)|20px||"{{ill|lt=Man'yoshu|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}" Volume 7 No. 1230<ref name="Complete Works of Japanese Classical Literature">"New Edition of Japanese Classical Literature Complete Works 7 Man'yoshu (2)” Shogakukan, 2004 ({{ill|lt=Japan Knowledge|Q11309996|WD=Q11309996|1=JapanKnowledge}} edition), pp. 226-227. </ref>}}
There is a song about praying to the god of the sea when passing Cape Kaneno (Kin no Misaki) {{Sfn|Kanasaki/Kanezaki (Heibonsha)|2004}}. Based on this song, there is a theory that Cape Kanenosaki was once inhabited by the Azum tribe, who worshiped the god Shiga. {{Sfn|Kanasaki/Kanezaki (Heibonsha)|2004}}.

